<article>
    <h1>SHINE LAN&#xAD;GUAGE</h1>
    <h2>Home-grown jew&#xAD;ellery and time&#xAD;piece fes&#xAD;ti&#xAD;val JeweLuxe is tak&#xAD;ing pop-up show&#xAD;cases and events across mul&#xAD;ti&#xAD;ple venues in Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore, in&#xAD;clud&#xAD;ing the heart&#xAD;land</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201204/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-04"><time>2020-12-04</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Amanda Chai</span>
    </section>

    <p>For the first time since it started in 2017, home-grown jew­ellery and time­piece fes­ti­val JeweLuxe will do with­out its main tent.</p>
    <p>In pre­vi­ous years, the lav­ish tent set up out­side Ngee Ann City was the main hub of ac­tiv­ity – host­ing fash­ion shows, keen col­lec­tors and jew­ellery houses from all over the world in 10 days.</p>
    <p>But with large-scale ex­hi­bi­tions out of the ques­tion this year, JeweLuxe, which started on Nov 1 and runs till Feb 28, now spans four months with up to 40 free events.</p>
    <p>The pop-up show­cases and events – each ac­com­mo­dates a max­i­mum of 20 peo­ple – are hosted in part­ner­ing stores like Lee Hwa Jew­ellery, Gold­heart Jew­elry, lo­cal jew­eller Caratell, El­liott & Car­men at the Raf­fles Ho­tel and watch re­tailer Watch Wonderland at Sun­tec City.</p>
    <p>Shop­pers can ac­cess the full sched­ule of events at jeweluxe sin­ga­pore.com and check out the fes­ti­val’s e-commerce plat­form JeweLuxe World (jeweluxe world.com) be­fore head­ing to the stores.</p>
    <p>Tap­ping the stores’ mul­ti­ple out­lets means the fes­ti­val is able to go into neigh­bour­hood malls such as Jem and VivoCity for the first time.</p>
    <p>JeweLuxe founder An­gela Loh, 53, says: “We’re work­ing with lo­cal re­tail­ers is­land­wide to dis­trib­ute the con­tent in dif­fer­ent stores. It’s a great con­cept, but our first time learn­ing how to be a dis­trib­u­tor.”</p>
    <p>MORE EVENTS, IN­TI­MATE SET­TINGS</p>
    <p>Ms Loh has em­braced as op­por­tu­ni­ties the many changes brought about by the Covid-19 pan­demic.</p>
    <p>Aside from the fes­ti­val’s change in for­mat, only 30 brands are tak­ing part this year, down from the usual 80 to 90.</p>
    <p>But this sim­ply means cosier events where brands can “get closer to the client”, she says. Each brand will get one event to it­self, ver­sus in the past where there might be 20 brands jostling for at­ten­tion at one event.</p>
    <p>“There was no chance for shop­pers to get to know the brand in a deeper way. And usu­ally there are a lot of peo­ple, so I don’t have time to get to know the shop­pers and hear their feed­back,” says Ms Loh.</p>
    <p>“This year, we get to know the real col­lec­tors – shop­pers who are re­ally in­ter­ested – and share in­sights. The deeper mean­ing of ap­pre­ci­at­ing jew­ellery can be more ef­fec­tively con­veyed.”</p>

